Nice Idea.

You can maybe reconsider the goalkeeper having two positions as it might make sense in code but as a previous comment has stated, him having "quantic behavior" doesnt make much sense. Instead you could think of changing it into a range in which if the goal keeper is standing up at x of 0 then it would make sense that he covers (0, 0) and (0, 1) or if he throws himself for the ball and ends up sideways he can cover (x, 0) and (x+-1, 0). This could increase complexity by having a more complex 'if statement' rather than multiple simple 'if statements'.

if i well understand.... before the shooter kick the ball the goalkeeper will be ready to throw himself in two different positions to grab the ball... those positions are represented by [goalkeeper1X, goalkeeper1Y] and [goalkeeper2X, goalkeeper2Y], if the ball is in any of those position is a INTERCEPTION for the goalkeeper, if the ball is outside the goal it's a OFF TARGET, or if the ball isn't in the position chose by the goalkeeper it's a GOAL...
is that correct?

1. Problem statement has to describe what the goal of problem is. E.g., 
"Your goal is to determine whether the shooter scored"
2. Problem statement does not explain why goalkeeper has 2 different positions at the same time. Does he move from position 1 to 2? Does it mean he can intercept the ball in all cells of his path or something else? Either way you should explain that.

Input
* Please add "space-separated" between "Two" and "integers" for all three descriptions.

* [[targetX]] and [[targetY]] are referred to both as the aim point of the shooter and also in a way that makes them sound like goal boundaries, which is confusing. Hence:
  ‚Ä¢ Please delete "(0 ‚â§ targetX < 7, 0 ‚â§ targetY < 3)".
  ‚Ä¢ In Goal section (not in Input section), please add:

The goal is represented as a grid with X-coordinates numbered from 0 to 6 and Y-coordinates from 0 to 2.

Output
* Please format "OFF TARGET", "INTERCEPTION" and "GOAL" as {{constants}} and remove the quotation marks.

Constraints
* Please delete the first two constraints because targetX and targetY may be outside the limits.

Cases
* Validator 8: Please revise the case to be more similar to Test 7, featuring negative target coordinates. Please remember that each test should be similar to the corresponding validator.

Thanks.

1-Yes, that's right, I will do that.
2-The goalkeeper prepares to intercept in these two positions, which he chooses in advance. So if the ball goes to one of these places, the goalkeeper will intercept it because he is ready for it. It's not about an instant t positions but a preparation positions.
anyways.... more test cases might be great!

This isn't a goalkeeper's quantum state. There's only one goalkeeper, but that goalkeeper mentally prepares before each shot. He think in 2 positions where the ball can arrive. If the ball really come on one of this places, he can save it on time. So the goalkeeper reactivity depend of his preparation.
The reason I included two positions for the goalkeeper to prepare for is to increase the goalkeeper's chances of intercepting.
